WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.700
Introduction to the Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus, translated

00:19.700 --> 00:20.700
by George Long.

00:21.740 --> 00:26.500
Introduction Marcus Arnius Verus was born in Rome in AD

00:27.240 --> 00:32.400
121 and assumed the name of Marcus Aurelius Antoninus, by which he is known to history

00:32.400 --> 00:36.000
on his adoption by the Emperor T. Aurelius Antoninus.

00:36.740 --> 00:41.860
He succeeded to the imperial throne in 161 and ruled till his death in 180.

00:42.820 --> 00:47.620
His reign, though marked by justice and moderation at home, was troubled by constant warfare

00:47.620 --> 00:52.340
on the frontiers of the empire, and Aurelius spent much of his later years in the uncongenial

00:52.340 --> 00:56.360
task of commanding armies that no longer proved irresistible against the barbarian

00:57.240 --> 00:57.510
hordes.

00:57.960 --> 01:03.320
Marcus Aurelius was educated by the orator Fronto, but turned aside from rhetoric to

01:03.320 --> 01:07.760
study of the Stoic philosophy, of which he was the last distinguished representative.

01:08.580 --> 01:12.840
The meditations, which he wrote in Greek, are among the most noteworthy expressions

01:12.840 --> 01:16.240
of this system and exhibit it favourably on its practical side.

01:17.100 --> 01:21.940
His own precepts he carried out with singular consistency, and both in his public and his

01:21.940 --> 01:24.660
private life he was in the highest degree conscientious.

01:25.720 --> 01:30.620
He and his predecessor are noted as the only Roman emperors who can be said to have ruled

01:30.620 --> 01:32.840
with a single eye to the welfare of their subjects.

01:33.900 --> 01:39.580
During his reign, Rome was visited by severe pestilence, and this, with reverses suffered

01:39.580 --> 01:44.300
by his armies, threw the populace into a panic and led them to demand the sacrifice of the

01:44.300 --> 01:47.840
Christians whom they regarded as having brought down the anger of the gods.

01:49.060 --> 01:54.180
Aurelius seems to have shared the panic, and his record is stained by his sanction of the

01:54.180 --> 01:55.060
cruel persecution.

01:56.220 --> 02:00.920
This incident in the career of the last and one of the loftiest of the pagan moralists

02:00.920 --> 02:06.880
may be regarded as symbolic of the dying effort of heathenism to check the advancing tide

02:06.880 --> 02:07.640
of Christianity.

02:08.540 --> 02:13.200
The meditations picture with faithfulness the mind and character of this noblest of

02:13.200 --> 02:14.280
the emperors.

02:14.280 --> 02:19.980
Simple in style and sincere in tone, they record for all time the height reached by

02:19.980 --> 02:25.520
pagan aspirations in its effort to solve the problem of conduct, and the essential agreement

02:25.520 --> 02:31.380
of his practice with his teaching proved that even in a palace life may be led well.

